jparsec.astronomy

Class CoordinateSystem

  • java.lang.Object
    • jparsec.astronomy.CoordinateSystem

  • public class CoordinateSystem
extends java.lang.Object
    A class to perform coordinates transformations. These methods take into account the equinox specified in the EphemerisElement object or epoch input value to transform input/output coordinates from/to that epoch accordingly (using IAU2006 algorithms). The frame is not taken into account, but note that equatorial to galactic coordinates should use the FK5 system as input coordinates. Methods to transform between different frames are available in Ephem class. The orientation of the galactic plane follows Jia-Cheng Liu et al. 2010 (see http://arxiv.org/abs/1010.3773), and since Sgr A is not at the center, a new definition of the galactic system is pending.

    The methods in this class are complemented by those in other classes. For instance, LocationElement can be instantiated using a body object to retrieve its coordinates, Ephem#toOutputFrame(double[], FRAME, FRAME) can be used for frame transformations. In case the object has proper motions and FK4 frame is involved, StarEphem class provides methods to account for proper motions.

    Version:
    1.0
    Author:
    T. Alonso Albi - OAN (Spain)
    See Also:
    LocationElement, StarEphem, Ephem

      • galacticToEquatorial

        public static LocationElement galacticToEquatorial(LocationElement loc,
                                   TimeElement time,
                                   ObserverElement obs,
                                   EphemerisElement eph)
                                            throws JPARSECException
        Transform from galactic to equatorial coordinates. The IAU 1958 system is used, established before the precise coordinates of Sagittarius A (the core of our galaxy) were known. The real center of our galaxy lies at -3' 21" of galactic longitude, and at -2' 46" of galactic latitude.
        Parameters:
        loc - Location object with galactic coordinates.
        time - Time object.
        obs - Observer object.
        eph - Ephemeris object. The equinox and frame fields are taken into account to transform results to output equinox and frame.
        Returns:
        Location object with the equatorial coordinates, respect to equinox and frame selected in the ephemeris object.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the date is invalid.

      • equatorialToGalactic

        public static LocationElement equatorialToGalactic(LocationElement loc,
                                   TimeElement time,
                                   ObserverElement obs,
                                   EphemerisElement eph)
                                            throws JPARSECException
        Transform from equatorial to galactic coordinates. The IAU 1958 system is used, established before the precise coordinates of Sagittarius A (the core of our galaxy) were known. The real center of our galaxy lies at -3' 21" of galactic longitude, and at -2' 46" of galactic latitude.
        Parameters:
        loc - Location object with equatorial coordinates, FK5 J2000 (or any other frame and equinox).
        time - Time object.
        obs - Observer object.
        eph - Ephemeris object. The properties of this object are used to transform input coordinates to FK5 J2000 (before going to galactic) if this is required.
        Returns:
        Location object with the galactic coordinates.
        Throws:
        JPARSECException - If the date is invalid.
